                                KeyShow

        KeyShow enables you to view the current keymap on your Amiga.
Double-click on the KeyShow icon and a window appears which shows the
layout of the Amiga keyboard, and the characters that appear when you press
qualifiers by simply clicking on the relevant qualifiers, or pressing the
qualifier keys on the Amiga keyboard. The qualifiers are the Shift, Ctrl
and both Alt keys.

        The keys are coloured to indicate what state KeyShow is in and how
the key combinations work. Qualifier keys not currently pressed are
coloured gray (or the background colour on your Workbench). When you first
open KeyShow the Shift, Ctrl and Alt keys will all be grey.

        Dead keys are coloured blue (or the Workbench highlight colour). A
dead key is a key which produces no character of its own, but modifies the
output of the subsequent key press. For example, on the USA keyboard the
Alt-F combination adds an acute accent to the next character (if the next
character accepts an acute accent). Thus by pressing Alt-F, then e, you get
e with an acute accent (e). KeyShow displays a key in bold-italics if it
canbe used in conjunction with a dead key.

        If it takes more than one character to define a key, the sign $$ is
display on the key. Characters preceded with a title (~) or caret (^) are
control characters. Blank keys are undefined by the currently selected
qualifiers.




